declare_parcel_as_script_with_stdin <<'/---'
Handle *list set variable declarators* (i.e., aliases declaring sequential array
variables ignoring duplicate array elements). Such variables are subject to the
same caveats and limitations as customary list variables, as well as implicitly
ignoring attempts to add items already in such lists. See @{list} for further
details.
/---

# ....................{ LIST SETS                          }....................
#FIXME: Define equivalent string_and_list_set_tied_on_character() declarators.
#As @{compile} demonstrates, "typeset -TU --" actually works (i.e., the "-U"
#properly applies to the list but not string).
:alias_simple.declare\
    'void :list_set(string variable_name1, ...)'\
    'typeset -Ua --'  <<'/---'
Declare the passed list set variables locally, initialized to the empty list.
/---

#FIXME: Excise after replacing with the prior alias everywhere.
:alias_simple.declare\
    'void list_set(string variable_name1, ...)'\
    'typeset -Ua --'  <<'/---'
Declare
/---

:alias_simple.declare\
    'void list_set_global(string variable_name1, ...)'\
    'typeset -Uag --' <<'/---'
Declare the passed list set variables globally _not_ exported to the calling
shell. See :list_set() for further details.
/---

# --------------------( WASTELANDS                         )--------------------
